1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 {The open Ruy Lopez was the tabiya of this match} 9. c3 Nc5 10. Bc2 Bg4 11.
Re1 Be7 12. Nbd2 Qd7 13. Nb3 {[pgndiagram]} (13. Nf1 {Kasparov says this move
is more energetic. I won't argue with the GOAT}) 13... Ne6 14. h3 Bh5 15. Bf5
Ncd8 16. Be3 a5 17. Bc5 {The most visible sign of Karpov relaxing after taking
the 5-2 score (remember that this game was played immediately after his  fifth
win in the 27th game)} a4 $1 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. Nbd2 (19. Nbd4 {Was better
nevertheless; this is how they played in the 21st century} Nxd4 (19... c6 {Is
the modern continuation}) 20. cxd4 Ne6 21. g4 Bg6 22. Rc1 {Gives White the
better chances}) 19... c6 20. b4 $6 {I don't like this decision} (20. Qc2 {
Seems more natural and is less commiting}) 20... Ng5 21. Qe2 g6 22. Bg4 $6 {
[pgndiagram] One small inaccuracy follows another} (22. Bd3 O-O 23. Qe3 Bxf3
24. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 25. Qxf3 Ne6 {And the knight is superios to the bishop. But
Black has only slight advantage}) 22... Bxg4 23. hxg4 Nde6 {Now Black's
horsies are quite dominating. h5 is very coming as well, opening the rook's
file as well} 24. Qe3 h5 25. Nxg5 {[pgndiagram]} (25. gxh5 {It is a natural
question whether White has to exchange queens} Rxh5 26. Nd4 Nxd4 27. cxd4 O-O-O
{But he only risks being mated as well. He has no counterplay on the queenside
(all a result of the b4 move)}) 25... Qxg5 $1 (25... Nxg5 26. f4 Ne6 27. f5 {
Is slightly unnerving}) 26. Qxg5 Nxg5 27. gxh5 Rxh5 {Now Black has more
pleasant endgame, as White's weaknesses on e5 and c3 are more tangible than
the one on c6. It is amazing to observe how Korchnoi manages to outplay his
highly skilled opponent from this position} 28. Nf1 Rh4 29. Rad1 Ke7 30. f3 Ne6
31. Ne3 Rd8 32. Ng4 Ng5 33. Ne3 Ne6 {[pgndiagram]} (33... d4 {Was very strong
here}) 34. Ng4 Ng7 35. Ne3 Nf5 {Winning the c4 for the rook, or forcing the d4
breakthrough} 36. Nc2 {White chooses to prevent the latter} (36. Ng4 {Is
probably more tenacious} d4 37. cxd4 Rxd4 38. Rxd4 Nxd4 39. Rd1 Ne2+ 40. Kf2
Nc3 {And there is still alot of work to do}) 36... Rc4 37. Rd3 d4 $1 {
[pgndiagram] This breakthrough is strong all the same. White is in serious
trouble} 38. g4 (38. Nxd4 Nxd4 39. cxd4 Rdxd4 {Is hopeless}) 38... Ng7 $1 {A
nicely calculated pawn sacrifice} 39. Nxd4 Ne6 40. Red1 (40. Nxe6 Rxd3) 40...
Nxd4 41. cxd4 Rxb4 42. Kf2 c5 $1 {[pgndiagram] The pawn chain starts moving} (
42... Ke6 43. a3 Rc4 44. Ke3 Kd5 45. Rh1 b4 {was also possible, but I like
Korchnoi's choice}) 43. d5 Rb2+ 44. Kg3 $2 (44. R1d2 {Is probably also
hopeless, but it is not immediately clear} Rxd2+ 45. Rxd2 g5 46. Ke3 b4 47. f4
gxf4+ 48. Kxf4 c4) 44... Rxa2 {With the fall of a-pawn, all White hope should
be gone} 45. Re3 b4 46. e6 Ra3 {[pgndiagram]} (46... fxe6 {Is probably even
more clear} 47. Rxe6+ Kf7 48. g5 (48. Rh1 Rxd5) 48... Rd7) 47. Re2 (47. Rxa3
bxa3 48. exf7 Rb8 49. d6+ Kxf7) 47... fxe6 48. Rxe6+ Kf7 49. Rde1 Rd7 50. Rb6
Rd3 51. Ree6 R3xd5 52. Rxg6 a3 53. Rbf6+ Ke7 54. Re6+ Kf8 55. Ref6+ Ke7 56.
Re6+ Kd8 57. Ra6 Rb7 58. Rg8+ Kc7 59. Rg7+ Rd7 60. Rg5 b3 61. Rxc5+ Kb8 {
[pgndiagram] Finally Karpov resigned. A brilliant technical achievement by
Korchnoi} 0-1

