1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Be2 O-O 6. O-O c5 {Having a
theoretical idea in mind} (6... Bg4 {Happened earlier in the match} 7. Be3 Nc6
{Is how the 18th game went}) 7. d5 $5 {An unexpected move for Korchnoi. Play
transfers from the Pirc defense to the so called Schmid Benoni} (7. dxc5 dxc5
8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Be3 b6 10. Rfd1 {Is what Korchnoi expected. One of his seconds
played this position later} Nc6 $1 {Solving Black's problems} 11. Rxd8+ Nxd8 {
Andersson - Stean, Münich, 1979}) 7... Na6 {With the standard idea Nc7-a6-b5}
8. Bf4 Nc7 9. a4 b6 {Preparing Bb7 with attack on d5, thus preventing e5 break}
(9... a6 10. h3 Rb8 11. e5 {Is unpleasant}) 10. Re1 (10. h3 Bb7 11. e5 {
Doesn't work here} Nfxd5) 10... Bb7 11. Bc4 (11. h3 Qd7 12. Bc4 {Would lose a
tempo compared to the game}) 11... Nh5 12. Bg5 Nf6 $6 {[pgndiagram] But this
is just bad. This is probably the move that cost Korcnhoi the match} (12... Qd7
{Continuing development and eyeing both e6 and b5 sqaures was correct. A
sample line can go} 13. Qd3 e6 14. Rad1 exd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Bxd5 17.
Qxd5 h6 18. Be3 Qxa4 {With equality}) 13. Qd3 a6 14. Rad1 {Now it is hard for
Black to find an active plan. e5 is strong} Rb8 (14... Qd7 15. e5) (14... h6
15. Bf4 g5 16. e5 dxe5 17. Bxe5) 15. h3 $2 {[pgndiagram] Too cautious, but the
stakes are high} (15. e5 $1 dxe5 16. Nxe5 {Is devastating, for instance} Qd6
17. h3 Rbd8 18. Bf4 Nfxd5 19. Qg3 Qe6 20. Nxf7 $1 {A nice blow} Qxf7 21. Bxc7 {
And Black is busted}) 15... Nd7 16. Qe3 Ba8 17. Bh6 b5 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Bf1
Nf6 {[pgndiagram] Now the situation is slightly better than it should have
been for Black. Still, White has the initiative} 20. axb5 axb5 21. Ne2 Bb7 (
21... e6 $5 {Was possible, taking advantage of White's delay} 22. dxe6 Nxe6 23.
e5 Nd5 24. Qc1 Re8 {And Black's position is viable}) 22. Ng3 Ra8 $6 23. c3 Ra4
$2 {A faulty plan} (23... Qd7 {Staying flexible was a better option and
defending f5} 24. Qg5 h6 25. Nf5+ Qxf5) 24. Bd3 Qa8 $2 {And now a decisive
mistake} 25. e5 $1 {[pgndiagram] Karpov has hesitated once, but twice he will
not..} dxe5 26. Qxe5 Ncxd5 27. Bxb5 Ra7 28. Nh4 $5 (28. c4 {Was very strong}
Nc7 29. Nh4 Nxb5 30. cxb5 Qb8 31. Qxe7 Bxg2 32. Nhf5+ gxf5 33. Nxf5+ Kg6 34.
Qxc5 {With a winning attack}) 28... Bc8 $2 {Game set and match for Karpov} (
28... Qb8 29. Qg5 e6 30. c4 Nf4 31. Qxc5 Rc8 {Would have still put up some
resistance}) 29. Be2 $2 {The stakes are high} (29. c4 {Once again ignoring
this move} Nc7 30. Qxc5 Nxb5 31. cxb5 Rb7 {With a won position}) 29... Be6 30.
c4 {Finally} Nb4 31. Qxc5 Qb8 32. Bf1 Rc8 $6 {[pgndiagram]} (32... h6 {
Preventing Qg5, was more prudent} 33. Nf3 Rc8 34. Qe5 Nc6 {And the win is
still not that easy}) 33. Qg5 Kh8 34. Rd2 Nc6 35. Qh6 Rg8 $6 (35... Ne5 {
Preventing Nf3, was CHESSENTIAL.} 36. b3 Rb7 37. Rde2 Ng8 38. Qc1 Nd7 {And the
play continues}) 36. Nf3 Qf8 37. Qe3 Kg7 38. Ng5 Bd7 39. b4 Qa8 40. b5 Na5 41.
b6 Rb7 {Back in those days the games were adjourned. Korchnoi resigned without
resuming} 1-0

